<section xml:id="section-assignment-week7">
  <title>Week 7 Assignment</title>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Invert these matrices. (Show the steps of your process, but
        you can use a computer for the row reductions.) (9)
        <ol>
          <li><me>
            \begin{pmatrix}
              0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \\
              -2 \amp 0 \amp -3 \\
              1 \amp 1 \amp 3
            \end{pmatrix}
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \begin{pmatrix}
              6 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
              -1 \amp 0 \amp 7 \\
              2 \amp -1 \amp -2
            \end{pmatrix}
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \begin{pmatrix}
              1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp -1 \\
              1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 1 \\
              1 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
              1 \amp -1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
              -1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
            \end{pmatrix}
          </me></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Consider the transformation defined by this matrix. (6)
        <me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            0 \amp -4 \amp -4\\
            9 \amp -1 \amp -2 \\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 5
          \end{pmatrix}
        </me>
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>
          What does this matrix do to this line?
          <me>
            \Span \left\{ \begin{pmatrix}
              4 \\ 0 \\-7 
            \end{pmatrix} \right\} 
          </me>
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          What does this matrix do to the plane given by this
          equation?
          <me>
            x + y + 2z  = 0 
          </me>.
        </p></li>
      </ol>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Consider this matrix and its associated transformation. (8) 
        <me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            -2 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\
            1 \amp 4 \amp -1 \\
            -1 \amp -1 \amp 2
          \end{pmatrix}
        </me>
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>
          Find a basis for the kernel and state its dimension.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          Find a basis for the image and state its dimension.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          Check that the dimension of the image and the kernel add up
          to the dimension of the domain.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          Find the rank of the matrix. 
        </p></li>
      </ol>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Consider this matrix and its associated transformation. (8) 
        <me>
          \begin{pmatrix}
            3 \amp -1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
            4 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp -3 \amp -3 \amp 1 
          \end{pmatrix}
        </me>
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>
          Find a basis for the kernel and state its dimension.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          Find a basis for the image and state its dimension.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          Check that the dimension of the image and the kernel add up
          to the dimension of the domain.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          Find the rank of the matrix. 
        </p></li>
      </ol>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        How many transformation <m>\RR^3 \rightarrow \RR^4</m> have a
        trivial kernel? What about maps <m>\RR^3 \rightarrow
        \RR^2</m>? What do these maps do, geometrically? (6)
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
</section>
